
<h2>
    Generic Fonts
</h2>
@{
    string[] fonts = {"Serif", "Sans-serif", "Monospace", "Cursive", "Fantasy"};
}
<ul>
@foreach (string font in fonts)
{
    <li>
        <span style="font-family: @font;">@font</span>
        <ul><li style="font-family: @font;">
            The Quick Brown Fox Jumps Over The Lazy Dog
        </li></ul>
    </li>
}
</ul>
<p>
    Font is important when making a website: it portrays a theme, 
    shows care and thought, but, more importantly, if a website is hard 
    to read readers will leave and not return. Font plays a huge role in how 
    easy or hard a website is to read.  
</p>
<p>
    Since there are a lot of fonts, most of which are restricted, it is a good idea 
    to have a few fallbacks and always a fallback to a generic font. This way, CSS has 
    a backup text that is available on almost all browsers to display when 
    the current font isn't supported.  
</p>

<p>
    The <code>font-family</code> property is used to change the font. 
</p>

<pre><code class="lang-css">p {
    font-family: /* font goes here */ 
}
</code></pre>

<pre><code class="lang-css">/* Example 1 */
p {
  font-family: "Times New Roman", Times, serif;
}

/* Example 2 */
p {
  font-family: Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif;
}

/* Example 3 */
p {
  font-family: "Lucida Console", "Courier New", monospace;
}
</code></pre>

